library(xlsx)

Read file Obs_expan_neuroforamil_height

#EXPANDABLE
obs_exp_neuro_height<-read.xlsx("Observational_studies_expandable.xlsx", header = TRUE, sheetIndex = "Obs_expan_neuroforaminal_height")
obs_exp_neuro_height <- obs_exp_neuro_height%>%
 mutate_at(vars(n1:sd2),  as.numeric)

#STATIC
obs_static_neuro_height<-read.xlsx("Observational_studies_static.xlsx", header = TRUE, sheetIndex = "Obs_static_neuroforaminal_h")
obs_static_neuro_height <- obs_static_neuro_height%>%
  mutate_at(vars(n1:sd2),  as.numeric)

Standardized mean difference Obs_expan_neuroforamil_height

#In the first step we use the escalc() function to calculate effect sizes and their variance
#EXPANDABLE
obs_exp_neuro_height<-escalc(n1i= n2, m1i=m2, sd1i=sd2, n2i=n1, m2i=m1, sd2i=sd1, measure = "SMD", data=obs_exp_neuro_height, vtype="UB",var.names= c("yi", "vi"), append= TRUE, slab =paste(Author, Year, sep = " , "), method= "REML")

#In the first step we use the escalc() function to calculate effect sizes and their variance
#STATIC
obs_static_neuro_height<-escalc(n1i= n2, m1i=m2, sd1i=sd2, n2i=n1, m2i=m1, sd2i=sd1, measure = "SMD", data=obs_static_neuro_height, vtype="UB",var.names= c("ys", "vs"), append= TRUE, slab =paste(Author, Year, sep = " , "), method= "REML")

#Using the effect sizes and variance we can calculate the random-effects meta-analysis
#EXPANDABLE
obs_exp_neuro_height2<- rma(yi,vi,data=obs_exp_neuro_height)
summary(obs_exp_neuro_height2)

#create a forest-plot using the forest() function
#EXPANDABLE
forest(obs_exp_neuro_height2)

#STATIC
forest(obs_static_neuro_height2)

#A common way to investigate potential publication bias in a meta-analysis is the funnel plot. Asymmetrical distribution indicates potential publication bias.
#EXPANDABLE
funnel(obs_exp_neuro_height2)

forest(obs_exp_neuro_height2)

#STATIC
funnel(obs_static_neuro_height2)
